comment.editorialComment: November is traditionally a month where things start to slow down a little, with showroom traffic slowing down and trade buyers becoming more cautious as we head towards the end of the year. Although volumes have been reducing in this sector over the past few years, this doesnt mean to say that it isnt immune from normal market forces. Reduced buyer activity and pressure on not having too much over-age stock at the end of the year all means that values are likely to move back a bit more than they have been doing in recent months. With this in mind, our forecast is that values are likely to move back by around -1.5% during the course of the month.

December is always a moth when the market comes under some pressure as retail footfall reduces and trade buying activity becomes more selective than ever. It is inevitable that values will come under some pressure during the course of the month and this sector will not be immune to that. However, over the years, volumes have been reducing in this sector and the balance of supply and demand remains fairly stable throughout the year. Wholesale vendors will still have product to sell and buyers will be out for most of the month looking for the end of the year bargains. Values usually move down by somewhere between -2.5% to -3.0% for this sector during December and we have no reason to believe that this year will be any different.

January should take care of itself as far as this sector is concerned. Given the reduction in volumes over the past few years then it is unlikely that there will be a surplus of stock. Demand however, will probably be fairly strong as the market gathers momentum after the Christmas break. Although the model choice is now slightly limited compared to some other sectors, they do represent good value for money and offer buyers a high level of spec and size compared to models from a lower sector. Our expectation is that values will remain fairly flat across most of this sector during January.
